Wash and dry all produce. Cut @Yukon Gold potatoes{24%ounce} into 1-inch cubes. Place
in a #medium pot{} with enough water to cover by 2 inches. Bring to a boil and
cook until tender, about ~{15%minutes}. Meanwhile, thinly slice @garlic{2%clove}.
Halve @grape tomatoes{8%ounce}. Pick half the @parsley{½%ounce} leaves from
stems and chop (save the rest for garnish).

Pat @pork cutlets{24%ounce} dry with #paper towels{}. Season with @salt{} and
@pepper{}. Combine @panko breadcrumbs{1%cup} and @Tuscan Heat Spice{1%tablespoon}
on a #plate{}. Season with salt and pepper. Evenly brush pork with up to half the
@sour cream{8%tablespoon}. Working one piece at a time, dip pork into panko
mixture, coating all over and pressing to adhere.

Heat a ¼-inch layer of oil in a #large pan{} over high heat (we used nonstick).
Once very hot, add 4 pieces pork to pan. Cook until golden brown, ~{2-3%minutes}
per side.

> TIP: Lower heat if panko browns too quickly.

Transfer to a #paper towel-lined plate{}. Season with salt. Repeat with remaining
pork.

Once potatoes are tender, reserve ½ cup cooking water, then drain and return potatoes
to empty #pot{}. Add @mozzarella cheese{½%cup}, 3 TBSP @butter{3%tablespoon}, and
remaining sour cream. Mash with a #potato masher{} until smooth. Add cooking water,
1 TBSP at a time, if needed to create a creamy consistency. Season with salt and
pepper.

Carefully pour out oil from pan used for pork, then heat pan over medium heat.
Add garlic and a drizzle of @vegetable oil{1%tsp}. Cook until fragrant, about
~{30%seconds}. Add tomatoes to pan and cook, stirring often, until they burst,
~{3-4%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper, then stir in chopped parsley.

> TIP: If the tomatoes won't soften, poke them with a wooden spoon to break them up.

Divide pork and potatoes between #plates{}. Sprinkle @Parmesan cheese{¼%cup} over
potatoes. Top pork with tomatoes. Tear remaining parsley leaves into rough pieces
and scatter over top.